---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import Boundary from "../components/Boundary.astro";
---

<Base>
  <!-- WHY: lead with the stakes. -->
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="eyebrow rise rise-1">The Human-Core Initiative</p>
      <h1 class="hero-title rise rise-2">
        Two forces are reshaping childhood at once, and most children are being
        prepared for neither.
      </h1>
      <p class="hero-lede rise rise-3">
        Screens are displacing the things that build a mind: attention, sleep,
        play, language, and real relationships. At the same time, AI now does the
        thinking that school was built to teach, and offers an easy way to skip
        the mental effort that grows a brain. Human-Core is one free, open
        curriculum, from the first months of life, that protects what builds a
        human and teaches children to master AI instead of being mastered by it.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions rise rise-4">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/curriculum">See the curriculum</a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/resources/screens-and-childhood">The problem with screens</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- WHY, concrete: the two forces. -->
  <section class="wrap forces">
    <p class="eyebrow">Why this exists</p>
    <h2>The ground under childhood is moving.</h2>
    <div class="forces-grid">
      <article class="force">
        <p class="section-no">01</p>
        <h3>Screens displace what builds a mind</h3>
        <p>
          A child's brain is built by movement, face-to-face language, play, and
          sleep. A screen does not add to the day, it takes the place of those
          things, and it is engineered to be hard to put down. The foundations
          erode while no one decides that they should.
        </p>
        <a class="text-link" href="/resources/screens-and-childhood">The problem with screens <span aria-hidden="true">&rarr;</span></a>
      </article>
      <article class="force">
        <p class="section-no">02</p>
        <h3>AI does the thinking that grows a brain</h3>
        <p>
          Learning is the residue of mental effort. For the first time a child
          can get the answer, the essay, the solution, without ever doing the
          thinking. Used as a substitute for thought, AI quietly weakens the very
          mind it was meant to help.
        </p>
        <a class="text-link" href="/resources/understanding-ai">Understanding AI <span aria-hidden="true">&rarr;</span></a>
      </article>
    </div>
    <p class="forces-close">
      Together, they put a generation at risk of being neither deeply developed
      as humans nor ready for the world they will actually live in.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- The belief / the turn. -->
  <section class="wrap turn">
    <h2>It does not have to be this way.</h2>
    <p>
      We know, from strong evidence, how humans actually develop and learn, and
      how to point technology at empowerment rather than harm. None of this is
      mysterious. What has been missing is a single, free, evidence-based
      curriculum that puts it together and belongs to no company. That is what
      this is, and the time to build it is now, while this generation is still
      young.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- HOW: the approach, principles with their reasons, stated once. -->
  <section class="wrap how">
    <p class="eyebrow">How we do it</p>
    <h2>One curriculum, built on what works.</h2>
    <ul class="how-list">
      <li>
        <strong>Protect the foundations first.</strong> Sleep, movement, play,
        language, and a present adult are what build a mind, so they come before
        any academics.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Knowledge before skill.</strong> You cannot think critically
        about nothing, so we build a deep base of knowledge first, and judgment
        grows out of it.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>The child does the thinking.</strong> Learning is the residue of
        effort, so anything that does the thinking for the child, a screen, an
        adult, or an AI, is removed.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Mastery, not avoidance.</strong> Banning AI leaves children
        unprepared, and surrender erodes them, so we teach them to use it, doubt
        it, and stay in charge.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Free and open, owned by no company.</strong> So any parent,
        teacher, or school on earth can pick it up and adapt it.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <a class="text-link" href="/principles">The full principles, and the reason behind each one <span aria-hidden="true">&rarr;</span></a>
  </section>

  <!-- The boundary: the signature, stated once. -->
  <section class="wrap boundary-section">
    <Boundary />
  </section>

  <!-- WHAT: the substance. -->
  <section class="wrap start">
    <p class="eyebrow">Where to start</p>
    <h2>The substance, free and without a signup.</h2>
    <div class="start-grid">
      <a class="start-card" href="/resources/pillar-1-curriculum">
        <span class="start-for">The spine, birth to twelve</span>
        <span class="start-title">The curriculum</span>
        <span class="start-body">How children actually develop and learn, age by age: the body and language first, then knowledge, then judgment.</span>
      </a>
      <a class="start-card" href="/resources/screens-and-childhood">
        <span class="start-for">For parents and teachers</span>
        <span class="start-title">The problem with screens</span>
        <span class="start-body">What devices do to a developing child, what the evidence says and where it is contested, and a practical plan by age.</span>
      </a>
      <a class="start-card" href="/resources/understanding-ai">
        <span class="start-for">For parents and teachers</span>
        <span class="start-title">Understanding AI</span>
        <span class="start-body">What AI is, the offloading danger, and why teaching mastery beats both banning it and surrendering to it.</span>
      </a>
    </div>
    <div class="start-actions">
      <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/resources">Browse all resources</a>
      <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/about">About this work</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  .hero {
    padding-top: clamp(3.5rem, 8vw, 6rem);
    padding-bottom: clamp(2rem, 4vw, 3rem);
  }
  .hero-title {
    font-size: clamp(2.2rem, 5.4vw, 3.9rem);
    max-width: 20ch;
    margin: 1rem 0 0;
    font-variation-settings: "opsz" 144, "SOFT" 0;
  }
  .hero-lede {
    font-size: clamp(1.1rem, 2vw, 1.4rem);
    line-height: 1.5;
    color: var(--color-ink-soft);
    max-width: 44rem;
    margin-top: 1.5rem;
  }
  .hero-actions { display: flex; gap: 0.9rem; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-top: 2.2rem; }

  section { scroll-margin-top: 6rem; }

  .forces { padding-top: 3.5rem; }
  .forces > h2 { font-size: clamp(1.8rem, 4vw, 2.6rem); margin: 0.4rem 0 0; }
  .forces-grid {
    display: grid;
    gap: 2.5rem;
    margin-top: 2.5rem;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
  }
  @media (min-width: 760px) { .forces-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 3rem; } }
  .force h3 { font-size: 1.4rem; margin: 0.6rem 0 0.7rem; max-width: 22ch; }
  .force p { color: var(--color-ink-soft); margin: 0 0 1rem; }
  .forces-close {
    margin-top: 2.5rem;
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: clamp(1.3rem, 2.6vw, 1.75rem);
    line-height: 1.4;
    max-width: 38rem;
    color: var(--color-ink);
  }
  .text-link { display: inline-block; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: none; }

  .turn { margin-top: 4.5rem; max-width: 44rem; }
  .turn h2 { font-size: clamp(1.8rem, 4.2vw, 2.7rem); margin: 0; }
  .turn p { color: var(--color-ink-soft); margin-top: 1rem; font-size: 1.12rem; line-height: 1.6; }

  .how { margin-top: 4.5rem; }
  .how > h2 { font-size: clamp(1.8rem, 4vw, 2.6rem); margin: 0.4rem 0 0; }
  .how-list { list-style: none; margin: 1.8rem 0 0; padding: 0; display: grid; gap: 0; max-width: 52rem; }
  .how-list li {
    padding: 1.2rem 0;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-line);
    color: var(--color-ink-soft);
  }
  .how-list li:last-child { border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-line); }
  .how-list strong { color: var(--color-ink); font-weight: 600; }
  .how .text-link { margin-top: 1.5rem; }

  .boundary-section { margin-top: 4.5rem; }

  .start { margin-top: 4.5rem; }
  .start > h2 { font-size: clamp(1.8rem, 4vw, 2.6rem); margin: 0.4rem 0 0; }
  .start-grid {
    display: grid;
    gap: 1.25rem;
    margin-top: 2rem;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
  }
  @media (min-width: 760px) { .start-grid { grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr); } }
  .start-card {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.5rem;
    background: var(--color-card);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-line);
    border-radius: 0.8rem;
    padding: 1.5rem;
    text-decoration: none;
    transition: border-color 0.18s var(--ease-out), transform 0.18s var(--ease-out),
      box-shadow 0.18s var(--ease-out);
  }
  .start-card:hover {
    border-color: color-mix(in oklab, var(--color-pine) 40%, var(--color-line));
    transform: translateY(-2px);
    box-shadow: 0 14px 30px -20px rgba(33, 28, 21, 0.35);
  }
  .start-for {
    font-size: 0.76rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--color-clay);
  }
  .start-title { font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: 1.3rem; color: var(--color-ink); line-height: 1.2; }
  .start-body { color: var(--color-ink-soft); font-size: 0.96rem; }
  .start-actions { display: flex; gap: 0.9rem; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-top: 2rem; }
</style>
